Changes a couple of things:
1. Adds repo_not_configured and pending_data_collection statuses to codereviewaudit.
2. Doesn't clear out errors when the remoteUpdate api updates a collector item.
3. Changes the reset logic for a collector item where instead of clearing all errors, it only clears the oldest one so as to drop it below the threshold count.

I use [cntlm](http://cntlm.sourceforge.net/) to connect to the corporate proxy and then just point maven at that. Unless you are behind a proxy, you don't really need a maven settings file. What issue are you having? 

```

<!--
 | This is the configuration file for Maven. It can be specified at two levels:
 |
 |  1. User Level. This settings.xml file provides configuration for a single user,
 |                 and is normally provided in ${user.home}/.m2/settings.xml.
 |
 |                 NOTE: This location can be overridden with the CLI option:
 |
 |                 -s /path/to/user/settings.xml
 |
 |  2. Global Level. This settings.xml file provides configuration for all Maven
 |                 users on a machine (assuming they're all using the same Maven
 |                 installation). It's normally provided in
 |                 ${maven.home}/conf/settings.xml.
 |
 |                 NOTE: This location can be overridden with the CLI option:
 |
 |                 -gs /path/to/global/settings.xml
 |
 | The sections in this sample file are intended to give you a running start at
 | getting the most out of your Maven installation. Where appropriate, the default
 | values (values used when the setting is not specified) are provided.
 |
 |-->
<settings xmlns="http://maven.apache.org/SETTINGS/1.0.0"
          xmlns:xsi="http://www.w3.org/2001/XMLSchema-instance"
          xsi:schemaLocation="http://maven.apache.org/SETTINGS/1.0.0 http://maven.apache.org/xsd/settings-1.0.0.xsd">
  <!-- localRepository
   | The path to the local repository maven will use to store artifacts.
   |
   | Default: ${user.home}/.m2/repository
  <localRepository>/path/to/local/repo</localRepository>
  -->

   |
   | Default: true
  <interactiveMode>true</interactiveMode>

   | Determines whether maven should attempt to connect to the network when executing a build.

   |
   | Default: false
  <offline>false</offline>
  -->

  <!-- pluginGroups
   | This is a list of additional group identifiers that will be searched when resolving plugins by their prefix, i.e.
   | when invoking a command line like "mvn prefix:goal". Maven will automatically add the group identifiers
   | "org.apache.maven.plugins" and "org.codehaus.mojo" if these are not already contained in the list.
   |-->
  <pluginGroups>
    <!-- pluginGroup
     | Specifies a further group identifier to use for plugin lookup.
    <pluginGroup>com.your.plugins</pluginGroup>
    -->
  </pluginGroups>

  <!-- proxies
   | This is a list of proxies which can be used on this machine to connect to the network.
   | Unless otherwise specified (by system property or command-line switch), the first proxy
   | specification in this list marked as active will be used.
   |-->
  <proxies>
    <!-- proxy
     | Specification for one proxy, to be used in connecting to the network.
     |
    -->

      <active>true</active>
      <protocol>http</protocol>
      <host>localhost</host>
      <port>8099</port>
      <!-- <nonProxyHosts>www.google.com|*.example.com</nonProxyHosts> -->
    </proxy>

    <proxy>
      <id>c1-https-proxy</id>
      <active>true</active>
      <protocol>https</protocol>
      <host>localhost</host>
      <port>8099</port>
      <!-- <nonProxyHosts>www.google.com|*.example.com</nonProxyHosts> -->
    </proxy>
  </proxies>

  <!-- servers
   | This is a list of authentication profiles, keyed by the server-id used within the system.
   | Authentication profiles can be used whenever maven must make a connection to a remote server.
   |-->
  <servers>
    <!-- server
     | Specifies the authentication information to use when connecting to a particular server, identified by
     | a unique name within the system (referred to by the 'id' attribute below).
     |
     | NOTE: You should either specify username/password OR privateKey/passphrase, since these pairings are
     |       used together.
     |
    <server>
      <id>deploymentRepo</id>
      <username>repouser</username>
      <password>repopwd</password>
    </server>
    -->

    <!-- Another sample, using keys to authenticate.
    <server>
      <id>siteServer</id>
      <privateKey>/path/to/private/key</privateKey>
      <passphrase>optional; leave empty if not used.</passphrase>
    </server>
    -->
  </servers>

  <!-- mirrors
   | This is a list of mirrors to be used in downloading artifacts from remote repositories.
   |
   | It works like this: a POM may declare a repository to use in resolving certain artifacts.
   | However, this repository may have problems with heavy traffic at times, so people have mirrored
   | it to several places.
   |
   | That repository definition will have a unique id, so we can create a mirror reference for that
   | repository, to be used as an alternate download site. The mirror site will be the preferred
   | server for that repository.
   |-->
  <mirrors>
    <!-- mirror
     | Specifies a repository mirror site to use instead of a given repository. The repository that
     | this mirror serves has an ID that matches the mirrorOf element of this mirror. IDs are used
     | for inheritance and direct lookup purposes, and must be unique across the set of mirrors.
     |
    <mirror>
      <id>mirrorId</id>
      <mirrorOf>repositoryId</mirrorOf>
      <name>Human Readable Name for this Mirror.</name>
      <url>http://my.repository.com/repo/path</url>
    </mirror>
     -->
  </mirrors>

  <!-- profiles
   | This is a list of profiles which can be activated in a variety of ways, and which can modify
   | the build process. Profiles provided in the settings.xml are intended to provide local machine-
   | specific paths and repository locations which allow the build to work in the local environment.
   |
   | For example, if you have an integration testing plugin - like cactus - that needs to know where
   | your Tomcat instance is installed, you can provide a variable here such that the variable is
   | dereferenced during the build process to configure the cactus plugin.
   |
   | As noted above, profiles can be activated in a variety of ways. One way - the activeProfiles
   | section of this document (settings.xml) - will be discussed later. Another way essentially
   | relies on the detection of a system property, either matching a particular value for the property,
   | or merely testing its existence. Profiles can also be activated by JDK version prefix, where a
   | value of '1.4' might activate a profile when the build is executed on a JDK version of '1.4.2_07'.
   | Finally, the list of active profiles can be specified directly from the command line.
   |
   | NOTE: For profiles defined in the settings.xml, you are restricted to specifying only artifact
   |       repositories, plugin repositories, and free-form properties to be used as configuration
   |       variables for plugins in the POM.
   |
   |-->
  <profiles>
    <!-- profile
     | Specifies a set of introductions to the build process, to be activated using one or more of the
     | mechanisms described above. For inheritance purposes, and to activate profiles via <activatedProfiles/>
     | or the command line, profiles have to have an ID that is unique.
     |
     | An encouraged best practice for profile identification is to use a consistent naming convention
     | for profiles, such as 'env-dev', 'env-test', 'env-production', 'user-jdcasey', 'user-brett', etc.
     | This will make it more intuitive to understand what the set of introduced profiles is attempting
     | to accomplish, particularly when you only have a list of profile id's for debug.
     |
     | This profile example uses the JDK version to trigger activation, and provides a JDK-specific repo.
    <profile>
      <id>jdk-1.4</id>

      <activation>
        <jdk>1.4</jdk>
      </activation>

      <repositories>
        <repository>
          <id>jdk14</id>
          <name>Repository for JDK 1.4 builds</name>
          <url>http://www.myhost.com/maven/jdk14</url>
          <layout>default</layout>
          <snapshotPolicy>always</snapshotPolicy>
        </repository>
      </repositories>
    </profile>
    -->
    
    <!--
     | Here is another profile, activated by the system property 'target-env' with a value of 'dev',
     | which provides a specific path to the Tomcat instance. To use this, your plugin configuration
     | might hypothetically look like:
     |
     | ...
     | <plugin>
     |   <groupId>org.myco.myplugins</groupId>
     |   <artifactId>myplugin</artifactId>
     |
     |   <configuration>
     |     <tomcatLocation>${tomcatPath}</tomcatLocation>
     |   </configuration>
     | </plugin>
     | ...
     |
     | NOTE: If you just wanted to inject this configuration whenever someone set 'target-env' to
     |       anything, you could just leave off the <value/> inside the activation-property.
     |
    <profile>
      <id>env-dev</id>

      <activation>
        <property>
          <name>target-env</name>
          <value>dev</value>
        </property>
      </activation>

      <properties>
        <tomcatPath>/path/to/tomcat/instance</tomcatPath>
      </properties>
    </profile>
    -->
  </profiles>

  <!-- activeProfiles
   | List of profiles that are active for all builds.
   |
  <activeProfiles>
    <activeProfile>alwaysActiveProfile</activeProfile>
    <activeProfile>anotherAlwaysActiveProfile</activeProfile>
  </activeProfiles>
  -->
</settings>
``` matthewbeasley

column2: Feature to score team dashboards - Overall score for a dashboard between 0-5 - Score for individual widget data: build, scm, quality, deploy Changes include - Score collector to calculate score for enabled dashboards (collectors/misc/score-collector) - UI widget to display and configure score - Core models, repositories & API changes Score Collector: - Collector will run periodically to calculate score for enabled dashboards - Configurations for score calculation can be set at default and individual widgets - Configurable criteria to set score if it meets a threshold. Flow to view score for a dashboard 1. Enable score widget by clicking on configure and save 2. After score collector has run, you should see overall score for the team dashboard 3. Details for score can be viewed by clicking `View Details` 4. Individual widgets will have score view, and clicking on it will show details of the score
column5: Feature to score team dashboards
column12: 372834245 @nireeshT based on our discussion have added changes to make score as a dashboard level configurable setting, with options to select the display in header or widget. Now, dashboard has new fields for scoreEnabled, scoreDisplay (HEADER, WIDGET) The score when enabled creates a collector item, and when disabled makes the collector item inactive. it will not be added as a widget in dashboard model 1. Create Dashboard has option to enable score The display options - Display in Header : This will display score in a separate header - Display in Widget: This option will display score as a widget in templates. It will be shown as first widget in top-left 2. Administer Dashboard has tab to view Score settings 3. Score Display in Header ![3_scoreinheader](https://user-images.githubusercontent.com/5722038/37372208-e2485b0a-2709-11e8-9847-e54ec4e26557.png) When score display is selected as header, it will add a header section to display score. The updated time is shown in right 3. Score Display in Widget When score display is selected as Widget, it will show score as a widget in dashboard. It looks like a widget, but doesn't have other options to configure and delete I'll do some cleanup today, but let me know your thoughts on this. thanks sidbha007 373041039 @sidbha007 I looked into it, all good. Awesome work!! While you are at cleanup, fix this undefined check. nireeshT 373113937 Thank you @nireeshT !! I have added a fix to show "No Details Found!" message in details pop-up when score data is not available. If you find any other issues, pls let me know, will fix them today. thanks for looking sidbha007 373506476 @tabladrum @satishc1 LGTM nireeshT 373510602 Looking good. Merge it! tabladrum 367122370 @satishc1 @tabladrum fyi, the PR to score team dashboards. sidbha007 367127521 +1 tabladrum 368051490 @nireeshT Please pull this pr down and lets discuss. satishc1 368634450 @satishc1 @tabladrum looking into it. @sidbha007 Good stuff !! nireeshT 369357012 @sidbha007 when I click on configure (gear button) on score widget, modal is displayed with save button. Will there be any configure steps listed or am I missing something or is it expected behavior. nireeshT 369365880 @nireeshT yes, the configure screen currently just enables scoring for the dashboard by clicking on Save button. I think adding some explanatory text might help "Click on save to enable scoring for your dashboard". If you have any ideas let me know, will fix it. thanks We had a way to configure scoring using custom Or default configuration. The default was picked up from configuration in scoring collector, and custom from configure screen. We removed custom option from configure screen, as while comparing dashboard scores default configurations made configs same for all. I did check-in the custom-config html file we had, but its not referenced in config.html : https://github.com/walmartlabs/Hygieia/blob/0c021beb2f9651de12aa38b3040a0f0e8a93fecd/UI/src/components/widgets/score/custom-config.html sidbha007 369370757 @sidbha007 - yep, got it. Scoring makes more sense when it is configured at the instance level. Just a thought, can we have score widget as view only on dashboard and enable widget on Administer dashboard modal by creating a new tab "Settings" -> Score (checkbox) on/off. Also can we persist all scoring properties into Mongo via JSON when ever collector starts and read the criteria from Mongo to calculate score. You have to setup rules in json and read through them to calculate metrics. Check out these files. https://github.com/capitalone/Hygieia/blob/master/UI/src/test-data/cicd-gates.json https://github.com/capitalone/Hygieia/blob/master/UI/src/app/dashboard/core/data-factories/cicd-gates-data.js nireeshT 369377344 @nireeshT having it enabled in administer dashboards sounds like a good idea. Thanks, will look into changing to this. For your second point, I am not sure if I fully understand it. Are you suggesting that scoring configuration is persisted in mongo, and score is calculated on UI based on the config? Like, we fetch the config and use the data in the dashboard to calculate score. If you can explain more, it would help. Thanks. I'll also look at cicd gates In current implementation, score is calculated and persisted for each dashboard and available via apis for each dashboard - The score apis for dashboard can be used in other places like Product dashboard, and we have internal team dashboards where the scoring is displayed. So, it doesn't rely on dependent data used to calculate score - The time range could be flexible, e.g we can use 30 days instead of 14 days to calculate score without changing in UI sidbha007 369653719 @sidbha007 Yes, if you could store the config in Mongo and read it from there to calculate score. I understand once the score is calculated for all dashboards, it is persisted into "score_metric". How about an objectId for scoreWidgetMetrics instead of widgetName here, because it solved future compatibility if we enable multiple same type widgets in a dashboard. That could mean multiple "build" widgets in dashboard and it will be consistent with data model. nireeshT 369975429 @nireeshT thank you for reviewing üëç Cool, so you are suggesting to have widget id in scoreWidgetMetrics instead of name. So, reason had kept id as widget name, as was thinking the score type could be for Dashboard, Team & User in future. With ids as "build, deploy, quality, scm", it works for any type. But, having widget id might be good for dashboard. Am, looking at it on how to change it to have widget. So, for the other point to calculate scores by persisting in mongo, are you thinking something like this - Collector starts and persists configuration - The same configuration is used to calculate score for dashboards in collector - have a api to view configuration So, by saving configuration we can read it from mongo using a api, instead of looking at config file. Just wanted to be clear, if thats the intent. will look at these, thanks sidbha007 370015470 @sidbha007 - yep, that is what I thought of persisting config into Mongo. nireeshT 370851401 @nireeshT i have added few changes, if you could have a look. thanks - Score metrics has field refId which will have widget id. In UI, refId is used to attach score for a widget - Scoring settings are now saved in collection `score_criteria_settings` and used to calculate score + API to access it https://github.com/walmartlabs/Hygieia/blob/cd9133d7ae2d28e976ecaf4407361c370ff5ab31/api/src/test/resources/score-criteria-settings.json - refactoring & cleanup sidbha007 370884622 @sidbha007 cool, will take a look. Can you ping me on https://gitter.im/capitalone/Hygieia, I can brief you about the change which I am working on and we can collaborate. nireeshT 370916947 @sidbha007 - I pulled the latest code base, I see github score metrics are missing. Is this expected nireeshT 370920353 @nireeshT i updated the property name in collector from `githubScmWidget` to `scmWidget `to be more generic. Srry, should have added in comments. Could you check if you are using updated scm property name `score.scmWidget` https://github.com/walmartlabs/Hygieia/blob/cd9133d7ae2d28e976ecaf4407361c370ff5ab31/collectors/misc/score/docs/3_widget_all_category_settings.md thanks sidbha007 370937880 @sidbha007 check these changes for getting score next to dashboard title. https://github.com/nireeshT/Hygieia/commit/74f09fa52df41e6e052f7e9d95e25a47027f4198 When I remove score widget from Capone template, I don't see individual widget scores. Anyways, these changes are rough draft though. If you see an option of moving the toggle to enable score to Administer- dashboard screen, this kind of display is possible and can get rid of score widget. BTW, on click of info icon will display scoreComponentDetails. Let me know your thoughts. nireeshT 371189140 @nireeshT I thought about it, IMO score as a widget has its advantages in usability It follows conventions of other widgets which makes it easy to answer some questions - What is this widget for -> Score (the header says it) - When was it last updated -> DateTime in upper right - How to see details -> "View Details" link is little more obvious - it could be activated/deactivated The score itself stands out as it has big size, with text for the score say "3.5". It grabs attention It is little easier to relate that the other widgets that show "star rating" are for the score. The disadvantage is the cost of space it takes on UI. I was thinking about the idea to put it besides title. In the dashboard page, the header has a bit of - Primary navigation (Hygieia Icon) - Secondary Navigation (Widget, Pipeline, Cloud) links - Title of Dashboard Putting score beside the title makes it bit restrictive in horizontal space. we could only put this much It is difficult to add text "score" or add few other details. Comparatively, it makes a bit harder to figure out. I thought about moving title on the page with score and tabs. Please check this. It follows the same conventions and might be little easier to understand but with same space problems, and not as clean when its shown in a widget. Another option could be to reduce space used by score widget. I do think it does look cleaner in the widget. But, I might be biased with the score in a widget as we have used it for a while internally and it has worked. sidbha007 371209415 @sidbha007 - I like both the options but I am some how inclined to first option. Reason being user can create a dashboard with variety of templates. Infact they can create a custom template. If we put the score widget in the existing standard template (Capone.html), they could have a score widget which they might not need on dashboard and there is no way to hide it. I am thinking if we could bring out both the flavors to ground. With the first option, if you could keep everything intact on header (Hygieia logo, dashboard -title and Widget, Pipeline, Cloud tabs) , use the space where you added title to display - " Dashboard Score i - "score value ng-rateit(your version of stars) ". This could be enabled/disabled with toggle from administer dashboard. Also I like the idea of last updated next to score. With the widget option, we can have a separate standard template - score**Template.html and you can add score widget in the layout. This way we can keep the existing templates intact and can have both the options. nireeshT 371236924 @nireeshT awesome, that's a great suggestion, thanks. i'll work on it üëç sidbha007 372834245 @nireeshT based on our discussion have added changes to make score as a dashboard level configurable setting, with options to select the display in header or widget. Now, dashboard has new fields for scoreEnabled, scoreDisplay (HEADER, WIDGET) The score when enabled creates a collector item, and when disabled makes the collector item inactive. it will not be added as a widget in dashboard model 1. Create Dashboard has option to enable score The display options - Display in Header : This will display score in a separate header - Display in Widget: This option will display score as a widget in templates. It will be shown as first widget in top-left 2. Administer Dashboard has tab to view Score settings 3. Score Display in Header ![3_scoreinheader](https://user-images.githubusercontent.com/5722038/37372208-e2485b0a-2709-11e8-9847-e54ec4e26557.png) When score display is selected as header, it will add a header section to display score. The updated time is shown in right 3. Score Display in Widget When score display is selected as Widget, it will show score as a widget in dashboard. It looks like a widget, but doesn't have other options to configure and delete I'll do some cleanup today, but let me know your thoughts on this. thanks sidbha007 373041039 @sidbha007 I looked into it, all good. Awesome work!! While you are at cleanup, fix this undefined check. nireeshT 373113937 Thank you @nireeshT !! I have added a fix to show "No Details Found!" message in details pop-up when score data is not available. If you find any other issues, pls let me know, will fix them today. thanks for looking sidbha007 373506476 @tabladrum @satishc1 LGTM nireeshT 373510602 Looking good. Merge it! tabladrum

column2:
I've recently run into issues when using [this plugin](https://github.com/spotify/docker-maven-plugin) to generate our images. This PR makes it so that you no longer need to use this plugin in order to generate images. This makes our approach more flexible as users now have a choice for how to build images. I think in the future we should deprecate the use of docker-maven-plugin in favor of [dockerfile-maven](https://github.com/spotify/dockerfile-maven).

Grievances against docker-maven-plugin:
- Builds stopped working randomly. Not sure exactly when this broke. I noticed this when trying to build images using a jenkins job. At first I thought it was a proxy issue until I deleted my local maven repository and the build started failing on my local as well.
- Requires external dependencies: Not only do we depend on the plugin for builds but the plugin itself has open source dependencies. This introduces unnecessary complication in an enterprise setting that seeks to reduce the risk of pulling in open source libraries. 
- This plugin does certain things behind the scenes. This means that the Dockerfile it uses isn't the only thing you have to worry about since in the background it copies files and stuff like that. This makes our Docker setup unusual and therefore more difficult to understand. We also give up a little bit of control for the sake of convenience and in my experience it's not that convenient. 
- This plugin is deprecated. Spotify themselves have stopped using it. You can read more about it on the [github page](https://github.com/spotify/docker-maven-plugin).

PR Contents:
- Add a Dockerfile to the root of every component (ui, api, api-audit, collectors). This let's you run `docker build .` in that directory and get an image.
- Add build directives for all services in docker-compose.yml. This allows you to run `docker-compose build` and have all images created at once.
- Change all the `x-properties-builder.sh` files to just `properties-builder.sh`. This makes it so that our Dockerfiles are more consistent. Also the prefixes weren't really adding to the readability since the file exists in the context of a directory therefore you already know what properties-builder you are dealing with.
- Add env PROP_FILE. This makes it so that the build can specify where the property file is located. The `properties-builder.sh` scripts now all use $PROP_FILE to know where to put the property file. This allows you to set the location of the properties file in one place and it's baked into the image itself. 
- Removed lines from the `properties-builder.sh` files that override $PROP_FILE. It's not clear what those were meant to accomplish and it's much cleaner to handle that in the Dockerfiles.

The Horizon:
- Use [dockerfile-maven](https://github.com/spotify/dockerfile-maven) to integrate image creation into the maven lifecycle. 
- Deprecate the use of [docker-maven-plugin](https://github.com/spotify/docker-maven-plugin).
 
Here's a screenshot of the failure of fresh builds. To trigger this you'll need to delete your ~/.m2/repository folder (scary, I know)
![image](https://user-images.githubusercontent.com/9603479/36325730-5adfef74-131e-11e8-9076-ea2ec01e061e.png)

column5: Jenkins build collector Root Certificate challenge
column12:
365930286 @pversteijnen Interesting. Can you try this on a non-docker jenkins collector. Alternately, check the java home(s) in your docker setup. Perhaps the collector is using a different jdk / jre than the one you are importing the cert into. satishc1
365958909 @satishc1 I have checked the Java_Home
```
root@2ba5ef71ef07:/hygieia# echo $JAVA_HOME
/docker-java-home/jre
```
Imported the certificate again:
```
root@2ba5ef71ef07:/docker-java-home/jre/lib/security# keytool -import -alias rootcarwe -trustcacerts -file /hygieia/RootCertificate_RWE_base64.cer -keystore jks-keystore -storepass changeit -noprompt
keytool error: java.lang.Exception: Certificate not imported, alias <rootcarwe> already exists
root@2ba5ef71ef07:/docker-java-home/jre/lib/security# keytool -import -alias rootcarwe -trustcacerts -file /hygieia/RootCertificate_RWE_base64.cer -keystore cacerts -storepass changeit -noprompt
keytool error: java.lang.Exception: Certificate not imported, alias <rootcarwe> already exists
```
No change and still the certificate error. Not familier with Java and I have the Docker setup so starting the collector without Docker is a challenge. But looking back at all the issues I have getting Hygieia up and running is nog giving me much confidence for the future.

Could be that I'm doing something wrong with the certificate? If I view the certificate path there are two certificates above the site certificate. I only import the highest level. Should I import both? pversteijnen
366983890 Solved it by creating my own docker image based on the hygieia source code. Added the certificates to a folder in the source tree and copy them to the container using the Dockerfile

```
FROM docker.io/openjdk:8-jre

MAINTAINER Hygieia@capitalone.com

RUN mkdir /hygieia /hygieia/config

COPY *.jar /hygieia/
COPY jenkins-build-properties-builder.sh /hygieia/

COPY certificates/ /usr/local/share/ca-certificates/
RUN update-ca-certificates && \
    ls -1 /usr/local/share/ca-certificates | while read cert; do \
        openssl x509 -outform der -in /usr/local/share/ca-certificates/$cert -out $cert.der; \
        keytool -import -alias $cert -keystore $JAVA_HOME/lib/security/cacerts -trustcacerts -file $cert.der -storepass changeit -noprompt; \
        rm $cert.der; \
    done

WORKDIR /hygieia/
RUN chmod -R a+x /hygieia && \
    sed -i -e 's/\r$//' ./jenkins-build-properties-builder.sh

VOLUME ["/hygieia/logs"]

CMD ./jenkins-build-properties-builder.sh && \
  java -jar jenkins-build-collector*.jar --spring.config.location=/hygieia/config/hygieia-jenkins-build-collector.properties
```

Big difference is that the certificates are changed to a der format. I think did was what I missed. pversteijnen

column2: If no scan data is present in the db then the "View All" button on the Code Quality widget will set an empty href. In this case when you click on the button it will take you the home page since the Hygieia UI is a single page app. This PR uses ng-href instead which supports expressions. So now if there is no scan data then caWidget.reportUrl will evaluate to false and no href will be set.

#Database Password - default is blank
dbpassword=dbpass

#Collector schedule (required)
feature.cron=0 0/5 * * * *

#Page size for data calls (Jira maxes at 1000)
feature.pageSize=1000

#In-built folder housing prepared REST queries (required)
feature.queryFolder=jiraapi-queries

#Jira API Query file names (String template requires the files to have .st extension) (required)
feature.storyQuery=story
feature.epicQuery=epic
feature.projectQuery=projectinfo
feature.memberQuery=memberinfo
feature.sprintQuery=sprintinfo
feature.teamQuery=teaminfo
feature.trendingQuery=trendinginfo

#Jira Connection Details
feature.jiraProxyUrl=
feature.jiraProxyPort=

# Trending Query:  Number of days in a sprint (not-required)
feature.sprintDays=60

# Trending Query:  Length of sprint week (not-required)
feature.sprintEndPrior=7

#Scheduled Job prior minutes to recover data created during execution time (usually, 2 minutes is enough)
feature.scheduledPriorMin=2

#Delta change date that modulates the collector item task - should be about as far back as possible, in ISO format (required)
feature.deltaCollectorItemStartDate=2008-01-01T00:00:00.000000

#Jira Connection Details
feature.jiraBaseUrl=https://<url>/jira
feature.jiraQueryEndpoint=rest/api/2/

#64-bit encoded credentials with the pattern username:password
#on a mac you con create them with : echo "username:password" | base64
#reference:  https://www.base64decode.org/
feature.jiraCredentials=<base64 string>

#OAuth2.0 token credentials (currently not supported in this version)
feature.jiraOauthAuthtoken=sdfghjkl==
feature.jiraOauthRefreshtoken=sdfagheh==
feature.jiraOauthRedirecturi=uri.this.is.test:uri
feature.jiraOauthExpiretime=234567890987

#Start dates from which to begin collector data, if no other data is present - usually, a month back is appropriate (required)
feature.deltaStartDate=2015-03-01T00:00:00.000000
feature.masterStartDate=2008-01-01T00:00:00.000000

# In Jira, general IssueType IDs are associated to various "issue"
# attributes. However, there is one attribute which this collector's
# queries rely on that change between different instantiations of Jira.
# Please provide a String Name reference to your instance's IssueType for
# the lowest level of Issues (e.g., "user story") specific to your Jira
# instance.  Note:  You can retrieve your instance's IssueType Name
# listings via the following URI:  https://[your-jira-domain-name]/rest/api/2/issuetype/
# Multiple comma-separated values can be specified.
feature.jiraIssueTypeNames=Story

# In Jira, your instance will have its own custom field created for "sprint" or "timebox" details,
# which includes a list of information.  This field allows you to specify that data field for your
# instance of Jira. Note: You can retrieve your instance's sprint data field name
# via the following URI, and look for a package name com.atlassian.greenhopper.service.sprint.Sprint;
# your custom field name describes the values in this field:
# https://[your-jira-domain-name]/rest/api/2/issue/[some-issue-name]
feature.jiraSprintDataFieldName=customfield_15433

# In Jira, your instance will have its own custom field created for "super story" or "epic" back-end ID,
# which includes a list of information.  This field allows you to specify that data field for your instance
# of Jira.  Note:  You can retrieve your instance's epic ID field name via the following URI where your
# queried user story issue has a super issue (e.g., epic) tied to it; your custom field name describes the
# epic value you expect to see, and is the only field that does this for a given issue:
# https://[your-jira-domain-name]/rest/api/2/issue/[some-issue-name]
feature.jiraEpicIdFieldName=customfield_11532

# In Jira, your instance will have its own custom field created for "story points"
# This field allows you to specify that data field for your instance
# of Jira.  Note:  You can retrieve your instance's storypoints ID field name via the following URI where your
# queried user story issue has story points set on it; your custom field name describes the
# story points value you expect to see:
# https://[your-jira-domain-name]/rest/api/2/issue/[some-issue-name]
feature.jiraStoryPointsFieldName=customfield_10002

# In Jira, your instance will have its own custom field created for "team"
# This field allows you to specify that data field for your instance
# of Jira.  Note:  You can retrieve your instance's team ID field name via the following URI where your
# queried user story issue has team set on it; your custom field name describes the
# team value you expect to see:
# https://[your-jira-domain-name]/rest/api/2/issue/[some-issue-name]
feature.jiraTeamFieldName=

# Set this to true if you use boards as team
feature.jiraBoardAsTeam="true"
```

I do not get any error just a 0 that is a bit frustrating I have no indication why it is not working?

Hi there, this project seems promising, but I'm having a really difficult time getting it set up using the docker-compose method. I have encountered several typos and unexpected errors along the way.

Particularly, the username and password used to setup Mongo and then access it from the API and from the Jenkins build collector don't seem to match up. Is the master branch supposed to work out of the box? I looked at and followed the documentation multiple times. Any help is appreciated.

Just for a start, I'm trying to get Hygieia running with just Jenkins, but the Jenkins container keeps complaining about Mongo auth failing. It appears that Mongo installs and runs with no blank username and password by default. But the `config/hygieia-jenkins-build-collector.properties` file was using a password. I have confirmed Mongo isn't using a password by trying to log into the Mongo container with a username and password, and it's denied. In the above mentioned file, I have tried blank creds:
```
#Database Username - default is blank
dbusername=''

#Database Password - default is blank
dbpassword=''
```
and also just commented out the fields
```
#Database Username - default is blank
#dbusername=''

#Database Password - default is blank
#dbpassword=''
```
but to no avail.

If anyone can share a link to a "working" branch, it would be much appreciated.
column5: Doesn't work out of the box?
column12: 369275852 @matthewbeasley can you setup a time with @ianrossi on gitter.im or google hangout and help with some of the issues. You can include me in the call if needed. Thanks. satishc1 369300491 @ianrossi - Do you have gitter.im? If so, I will message you directly on gitter.im to coordinate a meeting. matthewbeasley 369372268 @matthewbeasley Yes, I'm on gitter.im, thanks. ianrossi 369375059 @ianrossi - can you reach out to me there in a one-to-one conversation when you get a chance? In order to run the jenkins collector, rename this [file](https://github.com/capitalone/Hygieia/blob/master/docker-compose.override.example.yml) to docker-compose.override.yml and add the environment vars for the collectors you want to run (jenkins-build for example). You can find the env vars available to you [here](https://github.com/capitalone/Hygieia/blob/master/collectors/build/jenkins/docker/jenkins-build-properties-builder.sh). Our docker setup is currently a work in progress and you can expect it to change in the near future. matthewbeasley 365062768 @ianrossi - if this solves your problem to your satisfaction, please close this issue. matthewbeasley 365302370 @matthewbeasley This doesn't solve my problem. For now, I have left the docker-compose setup behind and have built the JARs on a Virtualbox VM and am running each individual process. I now have Mongo running, the API, gulp serve (UI) and the Jenkins build collector (against a local Dockerized Jenkins with 2 jobs) running and all logs seem to be running with no errors. However, I can't get anything to show up in the dashboard. I'm stuck on this: ![screen shot 2018-02-13 at 10 18 56 am](https://user-images.githubusercontent.com/103247/36157395-b0a6b3f8-10a7-11e8-9f91-aea2c086545a.png) First, **what does the format ` : ` mean?** I don't see any info in the docs about this. The gentlemen that posted [this video](https://youtu.be/Iq8M3llEp0k?t=1239) (over a year ago) doesn't show any special format for the job names, it's just the Jenkins job names. The logs for the build collector show this: ``` 2018-02-13 10:24:00,024 INFO c.c.d.collector.DefaultHudsonClient - Fetching jobs 0/2 pageSize 1000... 2018-02-13 10:24:00,035 INFO c.c.d.collector.CollectorTask - Fetched jobs 0s 2018-02-13 10:24:00,036 INFO c.c.d.collector.CollectorTask - New jobs 0 0s 2018-02-13 10:24:00,044 INFO c.c.d.collector.CollectorTask - New builds 0 0s 2018-02-13 10:24:00,051 INFO c.c.d.collector.CollectorTask - New configs 0 0s 2018-02-13 10:24:00,052 INFO c.c.d.collector.CollectorTask - Finished 0s ``` Previous reports like this showed when the `New jobs` were added. But what does this mean? The jobs should now be discoverable? Because they don't come up when I search in the above screenshot. I also keep on getting the [JWT error](https://github.com/capitalone/Hygieia/issues/1564) which makes things more difficult. Can anyone point me a to a known working walkthrough of how to get Hygieia set up in its current state? I have implemented a whole lot of different open source project from Chef to Sensu to Kubernetes and I'm kind of surprised that a project like Hygieia with Cap One behind it does not have better documentation. However, this is just an observation. Based what I've seen in screenshots, Hygieia looks to be a fantastic tools with lots to offer. Any help is very much appreciated. ianrossi 365320974 @ianrossi - can you be more specific as to how what I said doesn't solve your problem? The ui, api and mongo should start up with just `docker-compose up -d`. If this isn't the case please let me know. The JWT error is more than likely a cookie issue. If using chrome: go to [cookies](chrome://settings/siteData), search your cookies for localhost and delete that cookie. Should be good to go. This will happen when you go from the docker setup to running the jars AND your jwt has expired. If that doesn't solve your JWT issue then you need increase your jwt expiration time in your api settings. It's not clear to me exactly which issue you are experiencing but I'm confident that one of these two things will fix you up. ` : ` corresponds to your jenkins server and the name of the job you are trying to track, respectively. matthewbeasley 365323482 @ianrossi - also as far as the docs go -- hang tight. We are working to improve them. If you have specific suggestions then please air them out here as we'd love to hear your feedback. matthewbeasley 365323747 @ianrossi - actually don't air them out here lol. If you have the time and have specific suggestions, open a new issue. matthewbeasley 365326190 @matthewbeasley Thanks. Is this the DNS name/address of the Jenkins server? If you can give an example, that would be great. Thanks. ianrossi 365330093 @ianrossi - if you know how to solve the JWT issue then you shouldn't be seeing it. "jenkins server" does mean DNS name / address. If you are running jenkins locally in docker and exposing the appropriate port (8080 for instance) then Server name is `localhost:8080`. This should be available to you as a dropdown item though. Can you post your jenkins collector property file? It seems that you don't have that correctly configured. matthewbeasley 365338402 @ianrossi - You can assign nickname or nicename for jenkins instances so that when data is collected from multiple instances, you will know the jenkins instance - job relation. You can do it in 2 ways. 1) You can set below values in jenkins.properties (pull-based mechanism) jenkins.servers[0]=http://localhost:8080/ jenkins.niceNames[0]= give some nick name for 8080 - lets call it **ianrossi8080** You can specify multiple server instances and nicenames with index. 2) If you have Hygieia jenkins plugin installed on your jenkins instance you will see Global Hygieia settings under - Jenkins -> Manage Jenkins -> configure system -> Global Hygieia Publisher Settings (Push-based mechanism) You can refer https://github.com/capitalone/Hygieia/blob/gh-pages/pages/hygieia/hygieia-jenkins-plugin/hygieia-jenkins-plugin.md on how to build *.hpi file (Hygieia Jenkins Plugin) and install plugin to Jenkins instance. Pull based mechanism - When you start running Jenkins collector, jobs/build information is pulled to Hygieia and you should be able to search basing on 1) job name only ( here my job name is HygieiaPublic) 2) nicename : jobname ( Eg - nireesh : hyg) - it should match on partial search. We used ':' as a delimiter for nicename and job name. So if you want to search on both, make you include : in between. nireeshT 365671959 Hi @nireeshT CC @matthewbeasley Thanks for this info. column2:
Hi,

On days the sprint ends, the feature widget for Jira displays all 0's for all values regardless if displaying hours, story points, or issue count. 

Is this expected behavior? I am not sure how sprint information is gathered, but the tickets still have the "Sprint" tag for the closed sprint. I would think that displaying sprint information (regarding story points open, in-progress, and closed) would still be useful on the days a sprint ends. After the end date, perhaps displaying all 0's might be appropriate, but before and including the end date, that information still seems valid to display. 

Any help would be greatly appreciated, thank you.
column5: No Sprint data on Sprint end dates
column12:
367792933 Hi, @MarkRx @Sbrenthughes 

Just wondering if there are any possible insights into this? If this is expected behavior or not. Where is the logic for handling this? In the Jira collector, API, or does the UI handle that? Many thanks. 

To give some details regarding the issue, below are some images that I hope help describe the problem I am facing. 

This is how the feature widget appears (on days the sprint ends):
![feature](https://user-images.githubusercontent.com/2696304/36559397-b3260c92-17c2-11e8-902a-7c0d1ccc832a.png)

And here is a ticket that is currently "in progress", tagged with the sprint that ended (note, the sprint that just ended, is "sprint 28"):
![sprint](https://user-images.githubusercontent.com/2696304/36559621-663690ae-17c3-11e8-9988-bf711abc60a6.png)  e-macias
368153007 After further investigation, it appears that the logic for determining what to send the UI is applied in the API layer, specifically [FeatureServiceImpl.java](https://github.com/capitalone/Hygieia/blob/master/api/src/main/java/com/capitalone/dashboard/service/FeatureServiceImpl.java#L451) calls [FeatureRepositoryImpl.java](https://github.com/capitalone/Hygieia/blob/master/core/src/main/java/com/capitalone/dashboard/repository/FeatureRepositoryImpl.java#L27) to construct a query string that will determine which features belong to the current sprint.

However, it is unclear what is meant by "**_any_**" in the following statement: "A feature is part of a scrum sprint if any of the following are true: -the feature has a sprint set that has start <= now <= end and end < EOT (9999-12-31T59:59:59.999999)". Where are the "break points" of the statement, to determine if "_any_" part is true? Because it seems as if "end < EOT" will always be true. 

Yet the UI is receiving no values from the API. Looking some of the rest responses:
```
{"result":{"openEstimate":0,"inProgressEstimate":0,"completeEstimate":0,"totalEstimate":0},"lastUpdated":1519422312519}
```
and 
```
{"result":[],"lastUpdated":1519422312519}
```

By editing [FeatureRepositoryImpl's query build](https://github.com/capitalone/Hygieia/blob/master/core/src/main/java/com/capitalone/dashboard/repository/FeatureRepositoryImpl.java#L36) to evaluate 'sSprintEndDate' as less than the current date (rather than _greater than_), I can see what appears to be proper end of Sprint handling (see image below). Looking at some responses now gives:
```
{"result":{"openEstimate":6,"inProgressEstimate":12,"completeEstimate":42,"totalEstimate":60},"lastUpdated":1519422317357}
```
and
```
{"result":[{"sEstimate":"0","sEpicName":"Technical Improvements","sEpicUrl":"https://jira.com ....} 
``` 

Therefore my question now becomes, how should end of Sprint be handled? Is the change I made the correct implementation to take, or would you advice a different approach? Thanks.

**Code change**: ```{'sSprintEndDate' : {$lt : '" + currentISODateTime + "'}}```


![feature_update](https://user-images.githubusercontent.com/2696304/36619111-74dcab90-18a2-11e8-9f1b-92c6d088b54b.png) e-macias
368505400 Data will not show up for sprints if the sprint is over. You could change your sprint end date to be 11:59:59 and it should continue to show up the day it ends. 

If you were to make that proposed change then you would not see any data for active sprints as active sprints would be start date <= now <= end. What you have is start date <= now > end which does not make sense. MarkRx
368625186 @MarkRx, thanks for the response. I agree that my implementation is not the ideal solution. However, is there then a scenario where the "[ENDED]" tag will display?

In our current setup, there is usually about one to one-and-a-half days between sprints.  e-macias
368944535 Currently it appears to only show active sprints. I suppose the query could be changed so as to pick up the last sprint even if it is ended. MarkRx

column5: Cucumber Docker Report Failure
column12:
364468867 I was able to fix this,  so learning are 

1. Make sure the cucumber.json or report file is archived through Post-build action through 'Archive the artifacts'.
2. make sure cucumber.json is there in archive path 
3. if still does not reflect try tweaking into mongo, (sometime it behaves weird)  shzshi

column2:
Hi Team,

I want to know how to setup ldap connection in hygieia. 

Please help me if it possible as  i am not finding a proper answer.

Thanks
Ashissh
column5: Question for Hygieia
column12:
363321506 Add the following properties in your api/dashboard.properties file with appropraite values of your LDAP server.

auth.authenticationProviders=[Authentication types you would like to enable, defaults to STANDARD, ex: STANDARD,LDAP]
auth.ldapServerUrl=[LDAP Server URL, including port of your LDAP server]
auth.ldapUserDnPattern=[LDAP User Dn Pattern, where the username is replaced with '{0}']

--LDAP Server URL, including port of your LDAP server
auth.ldapServerUrl=[ldap://company.com:389]
 --If using standard LDAP
--LDAP User Dn Pattern, where the username is replaced with '{0}'
auth.ldapUserDnPattern=[uid={0},OU=Users,dc=your,dc=company,dc=com]

If you are using ActiveDirectory with LDAP add the following properties 

--If using ActiveDirectory
--This will be the domain part of your userPrincipalName
auth.adDomain=[company.com]
--This will be your root dn
auth.adRootDn=[dc=your,dc=company,dc=com]
-- This will be your active directory URL (required for AD)
auth.adUrl=[Need an example]

Hygieia Doc Reference link : https://github.com/capitalone/Hygieia/blob/gh-pages/pages/hygieia/api/api.md

After adding the above properties just run the api jar again and you will get an option of LDAP on the UI with default STANDARD (local) login.

![image](https://user-images.githubusercontent.com/16320111/35844291-c1f61380-0b32-11e8-82af-fd3f0ffb4398.png)
    ameetsvshah

column5: Bitbucket collector not using proxy settings
column12:
362258373 For now the problem is fixed for me. I added a docker container that deals with all proxy traffic. So I configured the proxy in one place and now I do not have to worry about proxy issues on collector level

More info: https://hub.docker.com/r/fengzhou/transparent-proxy/

```
  # Proxy
  transparent-proxy:
    image: fengzhou/transparent-proxy
    privileged: true
    network_mode: "host"
    environment:
      #This is upstream proxy, should support "CONNECT" HTTP method (Usually it is http proxy for HTTPS).
      - HTTP_PROXY=<proxy>:<port>
      #This is optional value to by pass network address without go through upstream proxy.
      #- NO_PROXY=
      #This is optional value and it can be any open port. Default value is "3129".
      #- LISTEN_PORT=
      #This is optional value, and should be different with other mark value used in iptables. Default value is "5".
      #- IPTABLE_MASK=
      #This is optional value for ports that can be transparent to proxy. The default value is "80,443".
      - PROXY_PORTS=80,443,22
      #This is optional value to start DNS proxy to help advanced filter by DNS. Default value is "53". To disable it use "0".
      #- DNS_PORT=
      #This is optional value to use advanced proxy routing configuration file. Default value is disabled.
      #- PROXY_CONFIG_FILE=
``` pversteijnen

column2:
The goal of this PR is make it so that a user can run `mvn install docker:build; docker-compose up -d` and have a UI, api, and a dev db. Then the user can rename the `docker-compose.override.example.yml` to `docker-compose.override.yml`, set the environment vars for the collectors they want to run and have those come up too. The compose file also maps the port of the mongodb in order to allow you to run the api or the collectors on the host machine if you are developing them. The api port is also mapped for development of the UI. The hose names have been changed to be the set to the names of the services. Docker Compose allows you to reference other containers via service name. The db information has been changed to match the docs. 

Future plans/ thoughts: clean up the `properties-builder.sh` files. The env var names are far too long for most of them. Also the way it currently works disallows optional env vars i.e all env vars must be set or lines must be commented out of the `properties-builder.sh` file in order for the collectors or the api to start. I was thinking of doing something like this:
```
if [ -z $ENV_VAR ]
then
  echo "collector.property=$ENV_VAR" >> $PROP_FILE
fi
```
However, I couldn't get it to work in time. The `Dockerfile`s themselves need to be cleaned as well. The `MAINTAINER` tag is deprecated for example. I would also like to add all the potential environment overrides to the override file to work as a bit of a reference to what all can be achieved

#Jenkins server (required) - Can provide multiple

#Pattern to find cucumber reports

#Another option: If using same username/password Jenkins auth - set username/apiKey to use HTTP Basic Auth (blank=no auth)
jenkins-cucumber.username=admin
jenkins-cucumber.apiKey=******************************
```

column2:
Who is responsible for updating the Docker Images in the public registry? These Images in most cases are updated one year ago. Can someone please update the Containers with the latest Versions of Hygieia?

We are using the Docker-Compose Approach to Setup the Hygieia Environment but it is not helping to have one year old Images.
column5: Docker containers are outdated
column12: 359906331 @pversteijnen - this is something we are working on. In the meantime, just clone the repo, run `mvn clean install docker:build` and you'll have updated images locally. From there you can push them to your own registry. Currently using our Docker images for production deployments is not recommended. Again, this is something that we are currently working on so stay tuned for a PR on this within the next couple months. matthewbeasley

359554817 @binnyg 
I think the issue may be that you have never run the Github collector even once before configuring the widget. And so the in the database there is no entry for the collector, and so the UI is failing.

Please run the Github collector once. 
From the path location "collectors/scm/github/target" under your hygieia installation:
Run the command: 
"java -jar ./github-scm-collector-2.0.5-SNAPSHOT.jar --spring.config.name=github --spring.config.location=<path to application.properties file>"

Make sure you have the following properties in your application.properties file.
These should be self-explanatory for the most part.
But if you do have any questions, please refer: http://www.capitalone.io/Hygieia/github.html

dbname=<database name>
dbhost=<database hostname>
dbport=<database port>
dbreplicaset=false
dbusername=<database username>
dbpassword=<database password>

logging.file=./logs/github.log
github.cron=0 0/5 * * * *
github.host=github.com
github.commitThresholdDays=15
github.errorThreshold=1
github.key=
github.personalAccessToken=

Any questions please let me know. Thanks ! subodhbattina

column12:
361185998 What worked for me was in the UI configuring set the API with my external IP address. Some how this solved my issue of not connecting to the API (using Docker-Compose)
```
  # Hygieia UI layer
  hygieia-ui:
    image: pversteijnen/hygieia-ui
    container_name: hygieia-ui
    environment:
      - jasypt.encryptor.password=hygieiasecret
      - API_HOST=<your external IP>
      - API_PORT=8080
    ports:
      - "8090:80"
    links:
      - hygieia-api
```

This issue can be closed pversteijnen

Before configuring the feature widget, you need to run the feature collector at least once so that the collector registers itself in the database. 
So in this case, if you want to configure a JIRA widget, then you would need to run the JIRA collector at least once, and then you will see this drop down populated. Thanks ! subodhbattina

column5: Using API to configure dashboard
column12:
359591881 @saxenadeepakkumar 
I am not sure if the APIs support programmatic configuration of the widgets via API calls. But please feel free to look at the code repository, at the path "api/src/main/java/com/capitalone/rest". All the rest controllers are in there. You could look into the relevant controller depending on the widget you want to configure, and see if the API supports the "create" operation or not.

If you are interested in contributing and adding this capability though, we do encourage that. You would need to fork the master branch and incorporate your changes, and create a PR for review after you have thoroughly tested your changes. Thanks ! subodhbattina
362719658 See https://github.com/capitalone/Hygieia/issues/1926. Documentation is currently in the works. Sbrenthughes

column2:
A slow GitLab server causes the Hygieia data collector to receive 'java.net.SocketTimeoutException' from the Spring socket logic.  This gets caught and rethrown as 'org.springframework.web.client.ResourceAccessException'.  This causes a stack trace in the collector.

Please find a TAR file attached with notes describing the problem in full as well as two patched source files and their originals plus two 'diff' views of the patch.

Here is the contents of those notes in full:
---
PATCH TO OVERCOME GITLAB SERVER REST API SOCKET READ TIMEOUT
============================================================

Trying to implement a GitLab data collector for this installation
of Hygieia had a rather interesting runtime problem.  The GitLab
the GitLab server could run quite slowly at time due to system
tuning problems.  Since a Gitlab server has a significant number
of processes running all the time, inter-process latency can be
signficant when other processing makes significant claims on
system resources such as memory and CPU time.  From a web browser,
the GitLab GUI would sometimes return an error 502 (bad gateway)
under these conditions.  From a REST API viewpoint, a socket read
timeout came back, generating the runtime exception
'java.net.SocketTimeoutException' event.  The Spring API translates
this into 'org.springframework.web.client.ResourceAccessException',
which may be caught by the invoking Java code at the point shown
below with a (++) marking.  The (---) marking shows the segment of
stack trace applicable to the patched code and creation and recovery
from the socket read timeout event:


2018-01-10 11:13:20,619 ERROR o.s.s.s.TaskUtils$LoggingErrorHandler -
  Unexpected error occurred in scheduled task.

org.springframework.web.client.ResourceAccessException:
 I/O error on GET request for
"http://gitlab.company.com:80/api/v3/projects
/root%2Ftest-GITDATA/repository/commits
/?ref_name=master&since=2017-12-27T11:13:00Z&per_page=100":

Read timed out; nested exception is java.net.SocketTimeoutException:
 Read timed out
        at org.springframework.web.client.RestTemplate
          .doExecute(RestTemplate.java:580)
           ~[spring-web-4.1.7.RELEASE.jar!/:4.1.7.RELEASE]

        at org.springframework.web.client
          .RestTemplate.execute(RestTemplate.java:545)
           ~[spring-web-4.1.7.RELEASE.jar!/:4.1.7.RELEASE]

        at org.springframework.web.client.RestTemplate
          .exchange(RestTemplate.java:466)
            ~[spring-web-4.1.7.RELEASE.jar!/:4.1.7.RELEASE]
---
        at com.capitalone.dashboard.collecteur.DefaultGitlabGitClient
          .makeRestCall(DefaultGitlabGitClient.java:92)
           ~[gitlab-git-collector-2.0.4.jar!/:2.0.4]

   (++) at com.capitalone.dashboard.collecteur.DefaultGitlabGitClient
          .getCommits(DefaultGitlabGitClient.java:69)
           ~[gitlab-git-collector-2.0.4.jar!/:2.0.4]

        at com.capitalone.dashboard.collecteur.GitlabGitCollectorTask
          .collect(GitlabGitCollectorTask.java:98)
           ~[gitlab-git-collector-2.0.4.jar!/:2.0.4]
---
        at com.capitalone.dashboard.collector.CollectorTask
          .run(CollectorTask.java:63) ~[core-2.0.4.jar!/:2.0.4]

        at org.springframework.scheduling.support
          .DelegatingErrorHandlingRunnable
          .run(DelegatingErrorHandlingRunnable.java:54)
           ~[spring-context-4.1.7.RELEASE.jar!/:4.1.7.RELEASE]

        at org.springframework.scheduling.concurrent
          .ReschedulingRunnable.run(ReschedulingRunnable.java:81)
           [spring-context-4.1.7.RELEASE.jar!/:4.1.7.RELEASE]

        at java.util.concurrent.Executors$RunnableAdapter
          .call(Executors.java:511) [na:1.8.0_144]

        at java.util.concurrent.FutureTask.run(FutureTask.java:266)
           [na:1.8.0_144]

        at java.util.concurrent
          .ScheduledThreadPoolExecutor$ScheduledFutureTask

           [na:1.8.0_144]

          .run(ScheduledThreadPoolExecutor.java:293) [na:1.8.0_144]

        at java.util.concurrent.ThreadPoolExecutor
          .runWorker(ThreadPoolExecutor.java:1149) [na:1.8.0_144]

        at java.util.concurrent.ThreadPoolExecutor$Worker
          .run(ThreadPoolExecutor.java:624) [na:1.8.0_144]

        at java.lang.Thread.run(Thread.java:748) [na:1.8.0_144]

Caused by: java.net.SocketTimeoutException: Read timed out

        at java.net.SocketInputStream.socketRead0(Native Method)

           ~[httpclient-4.3.6.jar!/:4.3.6]

           ~[httpclient-4.3.6.jar!/:4.3.6]

        at org.apache.http.impl.execchain.RedirectExec
          .execute(RedirectExec.java:108)
           ~[httpclient-4.3.6.jar!/:4.3.6]

        at org.apache.http.impl.client
          .InternalHttpClient.doExecute(InternalHttpClient.java:184)
           ~[httpclient-4.3.6.jar!/:4.3.6]

        at org.apache.http.impl.client.CloseableHttpClient
          .execute(CloseableHttpClient.java:82)
           ~[httpclient-4.3.6.jar!/:4.3.6]

        at org.springframework.http.client
          .HttpComponentsClientHttpRequest
          .executeInternal(HttpComponentsClientHttpRequest.java:91)
           ~[spring-web-4.1.7.RELEASE.jar!/:4.1.7.RELEASE]

        at org.springframework.http.client
          .AbstractBufferingClientHttpRequest
          .executeInternal(AbstractBufferingClientHttpRequest.java:48)
           ~[spring-web-4.1.7.RELEASE.jar!/:4.1.7.RELEASE]

        at org.springframework.http.client.AbstractClientHttpRequest
          .execute(AbstractClientHttpRequest.java:53)
           ~[spring-web-4.1.7.RELEASE.jar!/:4.1.7.RELEASE]

        at org.springframework.web.client.RestTemplate
          .doExecute(RestTemplate.java:569)
           ~[spring-web-4.1.7.RELEASE.jar!/:4.1.7.RELEASE]
        ... 15 common frames omitted

The patch provided here performs two actions on two files in the source
directory 'collectors/scm/gitlab/src/main/java/com/capitalone/dashboard
/collecteur' to patch the Hygieia 2.0.4 release branch:

(1)   DefaultGitlabGitClent.java:  Retry three times if this event
      arises as detected by catch(ResourceAccessException).  If
      detected, perform Thread.sleep() for RETRY_SLEEP_TIME_MS
      milliseconds between attempts.  If this Thread.sleep() is
      interrupted--which is most unlikely--a catch(InterruptedException)
      will retry the socket read without counting an additional retry.
      Once a valid socket read is detected or the retry count expires,
      continue with current processing.

(2)   GitlabGitCOllectorTask.java:  If no data is returned from the
      getCommits() method due to socket timeouts or simply no data to
      report, defer updating the Git 'repo' object with update times
      until that condition is known.  This way, if there is a problem
      with obtaining data during the initial attempt at data collector
      startup time, the 'firstRun' condition is preserved and the next
      scan cycle of the collector will request the larger amount from
      the 'firstRun' condtion.  If it is still not available, the next
      scan does the same thing until the GitLab server finally gives up
      and produces data.  This is likely to occur since system cacheing
      will make its memory and disk resources more quickly available
      on successive scans until finally data is returned, at least so I
      suggest and speculate. Once the 'firstRun' condition is satisfied,
      successive data collector scans will request incremental results
      per existing behavior.


RELATED DATA COLLECTOR ISSUES
=============================

It might be prudent for the other Git data collectors to investigate
whether or not this issue might affect them also.  If the GitHub
data collector were to be examined, an easy way to test it would be
to set both(?) the socket connect and read timeout down from 20,000ms
to 1ms.  This would guarantee the problem to exist.  I cannot
assume which one of the two timeouts is invoked but this would be an
easy test.  It SHOULD be the read operation, since the log message
said 'Read timed out'.  The 'java.next.SocketTimeoutException' would
most certainly occur on its first invocation.  If so, then this same
patch technique could be implemented to catch
'org.springframework.web.client.ResourceAccessException'.

All other Hygieia clients probably would stand an examination of their
read timeout conditions since the product is still quite new and usage
data from production conditions is not yet widely known.  I would
suggest that numerous other Hygieia data collector applications could
use the same scrutiny and possibly a similar approach to bolstering the
response of the application against socket read timeout conditions.


PATCH DATA AND REPORTS
======================

The following files are provided to describe and implement this patch:

notes.txt
---------
This text file.


gitlab-collector-raw.diff
-------------------------
Output of 'diff -r ORIG-src src' to show every change precisely,
including white space differences.


gitlab-collector-no-white-spc-diffs.diff
----------------------------------------
Output of 'diff -rbBw ORIG-src src' to show the same changes but
not include white space differences.


ORIG-src/2.0.4/collectors/scm/gitlab
/src/main/java/com/capitalone/dashboard
/collecteur/DefaultGitlabGitClient.java
---------------------------------------
Source code file 'DefaultGitlabClient.java' directly from 2.0.4 release.


ORIG-src/2.0.4/collectors/scm/gitlab
/src/main/java/com/capitalone/dashboard
/collecteur/GitlabGitCollectorTask.java
---------------------------------------
Source code file 'GitlabGitCollector.java' directly from 2.0.4 release.


src/2.0.4/collectors/scm/gitlab
/src/main/java/com/capitalone/dashboard
/collecteur/DefaultGitlabGitClient.java
---------------------------------------
Source code file 'DefaultGitlabClient.java' as modified for this patch.


src/2.0.4/collectors/scm/gitlab
/src/main/java/com/capitalone/dashboard
/collecteur/GitlabGitCollectorTask.java
---------------------------------------
Source code file 'GitlabGitCollector.java' as modified for this patch.


EOF

column2: The login page uses ng-show to hide / show the login forms for standard and ldap. This is problematic because both are loaded into the DOM. This is because ng-show loads the element into the DOM and then uses the condition provided to determine an elements visibility. If we use ng-if instead then the elements are only loaded into the DOM if the condition is met.

auth.authenticationProviders=LDAP,STANDARD

auth.userLastName=[name of the header containing user's last name]

column2:
This solves issue [#1856](https://github.com/capitalone/Hygieia/issues/1856). In the current state no matter what you attempt to set API_HOST to, you always get 'hygieia-api' as the hostname. In addition 127.0.0.1 is the current default which is rather useless as the api will never be reachable at this address.

The solution: remove the two export statements because they interfere with a user's ability to set the api hostname using ENV vars. Also change '127.0.0.1' to 'hygieia-api' since that hostname will be provided for you if you are using container linking or networking.

column12:
356946959 @rodrigocmn - thank you so much for this comment. You are right that the documentation is wrong in those two places. We will update it very soon. Also, thank you for sharing what you did to fix the issue on your end as this is very valuable information to us and the community at large. matthewbeasley 356949018 @matthewbeasley my pleasure! rodrigocmn 356953333 @hrushie, @alexandruivan - since @rodrigocmn was able to successfully set up his collector I believe this issue should be closed. If either of you still have issues please reach out to me at our [gitter.im](https://gitter.im/capitalone/Hygieia) channel. I look forward to talking to you there. matthewbeasley 356987247 @matthewbeasley just one last comment... even when I was getting the encryption error, the api layer was not throwing any error. I believe that is because the catch block in the EncryptionServiceImpl is using logger at debug level. ``` public String encrypt(String message) { String key = apiSettings.getKey(); String returnString = "ERROR"; if (!"".equals(key)) { try { returnString = Encryption.encryptString(message, key); } catch (EncryptionException ignored) { LOGGER.debug("Caught encryption exception", ignored); } } return returnString; } ``` rodrigocmn 356989660 @rodrigocmn - good catch, I think it should probably be `LOGGER.error()` or at least `LOGGER.warning()`. I'm going to submit a PR for this. matthewbeasley 353387423 @hrushie - I'm currently looking into this issue. We have not removed the documentation for creating an encryption key. You can find that [here](http://www.capitalone.io/Hygieia/setup.html) matthewbeasley 353388372 @hrushie - can you please provide additional details on the error you are receiving? A screenshot of your logs with your personal info redacted would be best. matthewbeasley 353393177 @hrushie - also check [here](http://www.capitalone.io/Hygieia/troubleshoot.html) for more info on github encryption for private repos matthewbeasley 353622718 [ Hi @matthewbeasley this is the error I am getting hrushie 354011000 @hrushie - Can you please provide the logs of the API when the error occurs. As I copied the command from the installation webpage, I didn't realise that it was a windows command and forgot to replace the backslash to forward slash (I'm running Hytgieia on RHEL). So it would be good for you to double check your start command. @alexandruivan Looking at the source code, I realised that you need to add the following property to your bitbucket properties file: git.key= I believe that [this documentation](http://www.capitalone.io/Hygieia/setup.html#encryption-for-private-repos) is wrong, as it says we should use the respective repo name as the prefix for the key property (i.e. github.key, bitbucket.key). I am facing issue in API - UI connectivity. API instance is running and am getting the response (response as true) when I hit http://localhost:8081/api/ping. I have deployed UI via gulp serve command and in the UI page its showing as no API connectivity. When I try to hit http://localhost:8081/api/dashboard, am getting empty json. From the API logs, I saw it has established connection to mongodb successfully. Can you help me to sort out this?

I have built the entire project successfully that I have cloned from GitHub. Mongodb,npm,bower installation -> successful. No error message in api log.

**command used:**

java -jar api.jar --spring.config.name=api --spring.config.location=/home/linux/.jenkins/jobs/Dashboard/workspace/api/api.properties

**api.properties:**
dbname=dashboarddb
dbusername=dashboarduser
dbpassword=dbpassword
dbhost=localhost
dbport=27017
server.contextPath=/api
server.port=8081
version.number=@application.version.number@

GET method http://localhost:3000/api/authenticationProviders & http://localhost:3000/api/appinfo returns 404 page not found response. But am getting response in localhost:8081/api/authenticationProviders as ['Standard'].

column2: As suggested in the [docker-maven-plugin docs](https://github.com/spotify/docker-maven-plugin) we should use [this plugin instead](https://github.com/spotify/dockerfile-maven). Doing so would allow us to bind our docker image creation (and optionally an image push) to a default maven build phase. I think the only functionality we would be losing is the ability to generate Dockerfiles which the plugin warns against and it doesn't seem like we do that anyway.
column5: docker-maven-plugin -> dockerfile-maven

column2:
Currently the Github collector won't pick up your proxy settings when running in Docker. We should provide a way for users to specify their proxy. One simple way we could do this is to look for an environment variable (e.g. GITHUB_PROXY) and then [here](https://github.com/capitalone/Hygieia/blob/master/collectors/scm/github/src/main/java/com/capitalone/dashboard/collector/RestOperationsSupplier.java) we can look to see if that ENV is set and if so, do something like [this](http://roufid.com/proxy-in-spring-resttemplate/). In fact, the Jira collector already does [this](https://github.com/capitalone/Hygieia/blob/master/collectors/feature/jira/src/main/java/com/capitalone/dashboard/client/JiraRestClientSupplier.java).

Currently there is a decent workaround. Modify the [Dockerfile](https://github.com/capitalone/Hygieia/blob/master/collectors/scm/github/docker/Dockerfile) and add `-Dhttp.proxyHost=<proxyHost> -Dhttp.proxyPort=<proxyIP> -Dhttps.proxyHost=<proxyHost> -Dhttps.proxyPort=<proxyIP>`
The whole command might look like this `java -Dhttp.proxyHost=docker.for.mac.localhost -Dhttp.proxyPort=8099 -Dhttps.proxyHost=docker.for.mac.localhost -Dhttps.proxyPort=8099 -jar github-scm-collector-2.0.5-SNAPSHOT.jar --spring.config.location=hygieia-github-scm-collector.properties`
column5: Github Collector in Docker doesn't pick up proxy information

348629892 vsnsurya: Please feel free to respond to Matt's question above. Also, please ensure the below listed properties are configured in your API properties file.

# [JWT expiration time in milliseconds]
auth.expirationTime=1200000

auth.secret=hygsecret
auth.authenticationProviders=STANDARD

# Configure below only if you are using LDAP for authentication.

#auth.ldapServerUrl=[LDAP Server URL, including port of your LDAP server]
#auth.ldapUserDnPattern=[LDAP User Dn Pattern, where the username is replaced with '{0}']
# LDAP Server URL, including port of your LDAP server
#auth.ldapServerUrl=[ldap://company.com:389]

# If using standard LDAP
# LDAP User Dn Pattern, where the username is replaced with '{0}'
#auth.ldapUserDnPattern=[uid={0},OU=Users,dc=your,dc=company,dc=com]

# If using ActiveDirectory
# This will be the domain part of your userPrincipalName
#auth.adDomain=[company.com]

# This will be your root dn
#auth.adRootDn=[dc=your,dc=company,dc=com]
# This will be your active directory URL (required for AD)
#auth.adUrl=[Need an example].

And then when running your API jar file, point it to your API properties file as below:
java -jar <file path to your api jar> --spring.config.location=<file path to your api properties file>.

Hope this helps ! Thanks. subodhbattina

column2:
Hi Team,

I want to setup Hygieia on my System using docker-compose. So, I want to pull latest images from docker public repository. But I found that latest/versioned images  are not available in docker public [repo](https://hub.docker.com/search/?isAutomated=0&isOfficial=0&page=1&pullCount=0&q=capitalone&starCount=0) (for example, [hygieia-ui](https://hub.docker.com/r/capitalone/hygieia-ui/tags/) image is pushed before 2 years). 
**Do you push latest images to docker public repo or any  other repo, when you released? So that, I can pull latest/versioned images from there.**
Otherwise, I have to setup Hygieia's code on my system and create docker images. In that case, I have to repeat this step whenever new released will be available.

Thanks,
column5: Pull latest docker images from docker public repository
column12: 348546395 Hey saxenadeepakkumar! Integrating a push of our latest images to Docker Hub into our release process is definitely something on our radar. As you correctly pointed out you currently need to pull the latest code from the repo in order to get the latest and greatest version of Hygieia. This will change sometime in the near future. Thank you for your feedback and do let us know if you have other issues with the docker set up. matthewbeasley

347966831 Help team... Naumansh
354357500 @Naumansh - in your jenkins collector properties file you need to specify the List index for your username and api key. So instead of `jenkins.usernames=Naumansh` and `jenkins.apiKeys=abceef` you need `jenkins.usernames[0]=Naumansh` and `jenkins.apiKeys[0]=abceef`. This allows you to have different usernames and api keys for each server. Basically the error log is telling you that it couldn't find credentials at the index that corresponds to your server. matthewbeasley

354363061 Hi @pasan96:
Following up on this issue:
After some research in my local environment what I noticed is:
In the mongo db, in the document "collector_items" there is a property called "description".
If that property has a non-empty value, you will most likely see the response coming back. On the other hand if the property is empty you will get an empty response.

If you manually enter any value into the "description" property in the database, you will see a response.
I am going to have to get back to you on how this value gets populated for different collector types in the database. Thanks ! subodhbattina
354363913 Its possible that at this point only the build collector has the logic to populate a "collector_item" record with a non-empty value for the "description" property, whereas other collectors don't do that and so don't have a response coming back. Thanks ! subodhbattina

column12:
347240922 Hey GPreksha! I have a couple questions:
Are you referring to /UI/src/components/themes/dash.less?
What gulp command are you using to serve the UI? matthewbeasley
347473362 Hey Matthew, i modified dash.css in \Hygieia\UI\dist\styles.
I am using "gulp serve" command for UI  GPreksha
347541639 Awesome. Gulp serve is the correct command. What "gulp serve" does is it takes the files in the UI/src directory, does some processing and then outputs those files to another directory 'dist'. So, if you modify the files in your dist folder they will be overridden the next time gulp runs the "themes" task. For more information take a look at the [gulpfile](https://github.com/capitalone/Hygieia/blob/master/UI/gulpfile.js) and look for the line that starts `gulp.task('themes', function() {`

tldr; If you want your changes to persist, only modify files in the src directory.

Please let me know if this solves your issue! matthewbeasley

After several tests I found out more things on Hygieia. It runs on EC2, CloudWatch and Autoscaling. It takes data from the billing dashboard on CloudWatch. How we can make our AWS collector to collect data from us-west-2 region

column2: We have two Hygieia env deployed in our docker infra. This hardcoded value in conf-builder.sh prevents us from being able to provide different API_HOST env variable for the two deployment.
column5: API_HOST is hardcoded in Hygieia/UI/docker/conf-builder.sh
column12:
349397507 Hey ibnjay! I'm currently looking into this. Are you using legacy container linking? matthewbeasley
351561572 @matthewbeasley Sorry didn't see that i already had a response. No not using legacy linking. Basically We launch the stack using docker-compose. Both instance of hygeia use the same network to expose frontend URLs. Using secrets we can configure API_HOST env for both stack differently. But the conf-builder.sh hard codes the value instead of just using the env variable. I suggest adding a check ```if API_HOST != null then export API_HOST=hygieia-api ``` Same thing for port.  ibnjay
